Looking at your code, I can see the issue with the map. The problem is in the map initialization timing and a missing CSS class. Here's the fix:

Replace this section in your CSS (around line 136):

```css
/* Fix map container */
.map-container {
    height: 500px;
    background-color: #e9ecef;
    border-radius: 8px;
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
    width: 100%;
}

#map {
    height: 100%;
    width: 100%;
    border-radius: 8px;
    background: #f8f9fa; /* Fallback background */
}

/* Ensure map tiles load */
.leaflet-tile-container {
    pointer-events: none;
}

.leaflet-control-attribution {
    font-size: 9px;
    background: rgba(255,255,255,0.8);
    padding: 2px 5px;
    border-radius: 3px;
}
```

With this:

```css
/* Fix map container */
.map-container {
    height: 500px;
    background-color: #e9ecef;
    border-radius: 8px;
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
    width: 100%;
}

#map {
    height: 100%;
    width: 100%;
    border-radius: 8px;
    background: #f8f9fa; /* Fallback background */
    min-height: 500px; /* Add this line */
}

/* Ensure map tiles load */
.leaflet-tile-container {
    pointer-events: none;
}

.leaflet-control-attribution {
    font-size: 9px;
    background: rgba(255,255,255,0.8);
    padding: 2px 5px;
    border-radius: 3px;
}

/* Add this missing CSS class */
.image-thumbnail {
    width: 100px;
    height: 100px;
    object-fit: cover;
    border-radius: 4px;
    margin: 5px;
    border: 2px solid #dee2e6;
}
```

The main issue is that the min-height: 500px; was missing from the #map element, which can cause Leaflet to calculate a height of 0. The image-thumbnail class was also missing and being used in the JavaScript.
